@Dan

Far be it from me to assail my idols,  Cox and Rathvon, on whose cryptic Atlantic crosswords I cut my teeth; but I would argue that a completely unassailable crossword clue might also be boring, wordy, uncreative or unoriginal. I would rather have a clue that amuses me and pushes the envelope, maybe takes a risk, rather than the same old same old.

That said, these clues are unassailable. SLIT is a verb which means to make a thin cut, which is what a letter opener does to open an envelope. It seems as straightforward a clue as can be. As for TESLA, whatever you or I may think about Elon Musk, Tesla is a large well known company filled with many hardworking engineers, factory workers and others who are just trying to put food on their families’ tables and, by the way, a quality product for sale. Don’t want to support Elon Musk? Don’t buy it. But eliminate the name of a legitimate company from crosswords? I disagree.

