@Matt
Conventional modern transliteration is "yəshaYAhu". As the Hebrew was shlepped through Greek and Roman mouths and ears, the -sh became an -s. (Cf. Hebrew [sh]abbat to English [s]abbath.) The terminal -hu was truncated into a soundless -h. (Same process turns yirmiyahu into Jeremiah.)
As for the change within English from Isaiah to Isiah, that may have been just an error or a deliberate parental decision to give him a unique name by purposeful misspelling.

@SBK in TO
I firmly believe that it's a misspelling on the part of the parent(s). It can't be pronounced in the traditional way without that "ai" combination. 

As someone whose name, Sheila, is misspelled all the time, almost always as Shelia and not Shiela, which would make more sense given the old "I before E" spelling rule, I've seen a few people working in stores with name tags stating their name is "Shiela." I'm pretty sure a parent misspelled it. While there are some variations, since it's originally of Celtic derivation, the two I listed are not them!

